EPISTLE XIII.

Tms letter professes to be written by Horace to one Vinius Asella, the bearet of certain volumes of his to Augustus at Rome, Horace being probably at his own estate. He writes as if he had given his friend particular and anxious instructions, when he started, as to how he was to behave, and as if this was to be sent after him, to overtake him on the read, in order to impress those instructions upon his memory. It is probable that some sueh jokes may have passed between Horace and his messenger when he started, and that he amused himself afterwards by putting them into the form of this Epistle.
